    • down puffy jacket or fleece jacket
    • hard shell outer layer (jacket that is wind and waterproof)
    • fleece hat
    • fleece gloves
    • rain jacket / rain gear (goretex or pertex)
    • 3 pairs of socks (you may end up wearing 2 pairs at the same time / one pair extra in case you get wet)

meta_value: After you've conquered those midterm blues, join us for a weekend exploring the beautiful, bizarro world of the Mojave National Preserve. This massive desert preserve may just be one of the West's best kept secrets. We'll depart Friday afternoon and spend our weekend exploring massive "singing" sand dunes, lava tubes, abandoned mines, Joshua Tree forests, and so much more. At night, we'll camp in the desert backcountry under one of the darkest night skies in the country. This is one you're not going to want to miss.

Join Peaks and legendary Professor Karin Huebner for an equally legendary Halloweekend under the Joshua Tree stars. We'll spend Friday and Saturday night in one of California's most renowned national parks, arriving Friday and waking up early the next morning to backpack 14 miles through Joshua Tree's backcountry. On our trek through the Boy Scout and Willow Hole Trails, we'll explore the Wonderland of Rocks and pass through multiple Mojave Desert ecosystems, witnessing a huge range of cacti, trees, and terrain. If you're up for a challenge and want to experience Joshua Tree as most have never experienced it before, you won't want to miss this trip!
Gigantic granite boulders, yuccas, cacti, scenic washes, and of course forests of the Joshua Tree itself.

Willow Hole (where we'll be hiking) is one of many potential water sources in the Wonderland of Rocks, creating a micro-habitat that supports an abundance of plant and animal life. If we get lucky we might see one of the Bighorn Sheep that call this area home!

In 1996, USA Today included the Echo Mountain hike as one of the “10 Great North American Hikes.” It’s got incredible views and ends at the old Echo Mountain House ruins (3,207 feet). In this hike, we'll be hiking Echo Mountain and going beyond to Inspiration Point.

Come hike to Inspiration Point and be inspired by Casey Schreiner, founder and editor-in-chief of Modern Hiker, in our first installment of Peaks and Professionals. Peaks and Professionals is our brand-new initiative where we plan hikes with professionals who have successfully incorporated nature and the outdoors into their professional careers. Casey Schreiner is the one-man show behind Modern Hiker, an outdoors website that details a dizzying number of hikes in the Southern California area. It's how we decide where to hike and we're stoked to talk with him about his experiences. We'll even be raffling off a signed copy of his book about hikes all over California. meta_value: Explore the Santa Monica Mountains and learn about a little-known but powerful piece of Los Angeles history on this hike with beloved professor Paul Lerner! We'll start off by climbing the lush Los Liones Canyon Trail, which culminates in beautiful views of the Pacific Ocean. Following the hike, we'll visit the nearby Villa Aurora, an artists' residence that was formerly the home of Marta & Lion Feuchtwanger, a Jewish-German couple who fled Germany in the 1930s (Lion was later labelled "Enemy Number One of the German People" by the Nazi regime). Their home in the Pacific Palisades became a gathering place for German-speaking émigrés in Los Angeles, hosting influential guests such as Charlie Chaplin, Thomas and Heinrich Mann, Bertolt Brecht, Bruno Frank, and many more artists and intellectuals. Professor Lerner's current research focuses on this vibrant exile community, making him the perfect guide for a trip that explores not only the natural beauty but also the incredible underlying cultural and historical significance of the Pacific Palisades.

meta_value: Escape the busy city and join us for a scenic hike in the Santa Monica Mountains with ocean views the entire way! The Parker Mesa Overlook sits high above the Pacific Palisades and PCH -- on a clear day you can see all the way from Downtown to Catalina Island! We'll start our hike on Paseo Miramar, a winding road off of PCH with some beautiful houses and views. We'll quickly reach the Topanga fire-road and start hitting some hills! The ascent to Parker Mesa Overlook is moderately steep in the beginning, but we stay on a fire-road for most of the time, and with some good company and great views you won't even notice how hard you're working! After about a mile uphill, we reach a downhill slope into Topanga Canyon. We lose the ocean view for a little bit here, but the shady trees and flowers of Topanga Canyon are beautiful as well! The downhill is brief, and we'll quickly turn a corner and start our uphill journey once more! It's only about 3/4 of a mile until we reach the overlook -- there's a sweet little bench at the top that's great for pictures. Relax, take in the views, eat some lunch, and then we'll begin our journey back down! The trail is out and back, so we'll go down the same way we came up. We'll connect back to Paseo Miramar for a total of 5.5 beautiful miles!

Accompanied by novelist, screenwriter, and USC writing professor Matthew Manson, we'll spend this Sunday poking through Mentryville, one of California's OG oil boom towns. As it's the first Sunday of the month, we can expect volunteers from the historical society to be present for "interpretive tours," which might be neat for some of you nerds. We'll eat lunch in the most flowery meadow atop the tallest hill, with expansive views of the Santa Susana mountains. Then we'll tackle some adventure terrain through Hughes Canyon on the return trip. With this cool a professor and hike - and this high a chance of ghost encounters - we're sure to have an epic day.

Be prepared for a wide variety of scenery! Potential views all the way to the ocean on clear days, panoramic views from atop eagle rock, and so much more!
The word Topanga is an old Shoshonean language word meaning 'above' and referring to the canyon settlement being above the flood waters of Topanga Creek.

This day hike, in the San Gabriel Mountains, boasts stellar views at Inspiration Point, with markers noting landmarks in the hustle and bustle far below. In an unconventional approach- we'll start at the top, work our way down 3.5 or so miles, have lunch while we swap terrifying tales, and then venture back up to where we started- perhaps a little sweaty and maybe a little spooked.

The U. S. Forest service in a tag-team effort with the Pacific Railroad Society has installed more than 30 interpretive signs in the Mt. Lowe Railway Area. Nothing like reading while you hike!

meta_value: Get ready to see the San Jacinto Wilderness from the granite monolith, Tahquitz Peak. We will enjoy a scenic alpine stretch of the Pacific Crest Trail with expansive views south over San Diego and Temecula, east to the Sonoran Desert, and west to the Los Angeles basin. At 8828 feet, Tahquitz Peak lookout is the second highest lookout in California!

Tahquitz Peak is said to be named for a leader of the Soboba Indians, Chief Tahquitz, about whom there are various legends. In one particular story, after changing from a loved to a hated chief as a result of evil spirits, Tahquitz' body was destroyed by his tribe, but his spirit escaped to the present Tahquitz Peak.

Join him to come discuss regenerative medicine, to enjoy a beautiful hike, and hang out with some like-minded people.

Mountains! Creeks! Flowing and falling water!

Mount Williamson is an 8,214' summit located in the Angeles National Forest. When standing on the summit looking north, it offers sweeping views of the Devil's Punchbowl, San Andreas Rift Zone, and Mojave Desert. This makes it a popular place for hikers to enjoy an amazing view of many interesting locations. Its distance from the general population helps to keep the number of hikers lower than in the front range of the San Gabriels.
From the summit and the Pleasant View Ridge, you can see the remains of a C-119 that crashed into Pallet Mountain in 1966.

Come join us on an adventure to the Devil's Punchbowl where the San Andreas fault has crumpled up rock layers into a maze of canyons and cliffs. The punchbowl is located in a unique area where the San Gabriel mountains are transitioning into the Mojave Desert where Joshua Trees grow. We'll enjoy Saturday afternoon cooking and hanging out at the South Fork campground before resting up under the stars for our big hike on Sunday.
Crazy tilted rock layers where the mountains meet the desert!
The San Andreas, Pinyon, and Punchbowl faults all worked together to shape this unique landscape!

What better way to kick off 2015 than a hike with Peaks and Professors? This kick-ass spring semester kick-off can help you keep your New Year's resolutions of exploring nature/staying fit/meeting new people/all of the above...and we've got a fantastic new professor joining us on his first P&P hike ever: Professor John Monterosso! meta_value: As Peaks and Professors trips have proved time and time again, L.A. is surrounded by some quite pristine wilderness. With that wilderness itself surrounded by civilization, though, it can be hard to carve out these slices of nature. Come see what it's like to watch over one such area - Portueguese Bend Reserve - and do so with a professor of Urban Planning - Dowell Myers. Myers is an expert in urban demographics and change, running an active research group that examines the ever-shifting makeup of the U.S. and its cities. One of Price's best, Myers will accompany us through some rolling hills and small cliffs, with views of the ocean, and great discussions.

We will begin our trip at the historic Neptune Fountain in Malaga Cove Plaza. From there we will venture up along the cliffs and hills above Malaga Cove where we will be afforded jaw-dropping views of surfers, a shipwreck and wildlife. Binoculars are encouraged! We'll end our trip with some coffee and late breakfast. Bring shoes you don't mind getting dirty and sandy!

Come get to know Professor of OT Kim Eggleston in the San Gabriel Mountains! We will hike to Switzer Falls, a 50-ft waterfall known as one of the most beautiful in SoCal. This moderately easy hike is 50% shade, 50% sunny, and 100% unique!

You made it to USC, now conquer Los Angeles's highest peak! With 3018 feet of elevation gain on a nearly mile-high peak, Mount Lukens boasts magnificent views of Los Angeles County. Joining us will be Professor Larry Harris, the Fred V. Keenan Chair in Finance at the USC Marshall School of Business.

For those of you who like some fantastic spring scenery with just a little bit of effort - this one's for you. A very quick 2 mile hike takes us to Bonita Falls (a fairly impressive falls in a normal year), with Professor Gail Borden - practicing architect, professor, and faculty master, as well as your conversationalist for the day. Join us!

meta_value: Oh yeah! First OVERNIGHT! We will be hiking through Angeles National Forest on part of the Pacific Crest Trail, which spans from Mexico to Canada. Early departure Saturday morning, driving to the trailhead and hiking through the San Gabriel Mountains about 8 miles on Day 1, stopping for lunch and summiting Mt. Hillyer to enjoy sweeping canyon views along the way. We’ll set up camp at one of the area’s many campgrounds, cook our own dinner and enjoy a night under the stars (remember <strong><a href="http://vimeo.com/83436955" target="blank">stars?</a></strong> *sigh* I remember stars). In the morning we’ll complete our loop back to the trailhead and expect to get back to campus by mid-afternoon on Sunday. This will be a moderately strenuous but lengthy hike, and you must be comfortable with roughing it a little (sleeping in a tent, carrying your sleeping bag, getting cozy with whatever insects we might encounter…)

meta_value: The first hike of Semester #2 for Peaks and Professors will be a gorgeous and quite easy hike, with a professor who hopes to make you think a bit. Vasquez Rocks is only an hour from L.A., and right off the 14 highway, but the scenery is out of this world. Our professor, Sharon Lloyd, is an expert in political philosophy, using everything from sci-fi to incredible thinkers like Hobbes and John Rawls (her personal mentor) to make students think critically. Get ready to ponder politics and revel in the rocks.

A great day of hiking, kicking back on the beach, exploring marine diversity, and learning from the outdoorsy and knowledgeable Professor Karla Heidelberg. We'll be heading to Abalone Cove Ecological Reserve, to tackle its moderate hikes, and then to enjoy some excellent tidepools. Professor Heidelberg, a biology expert, will be showing us around the two beaches, and, in a first for Peaks and Professors, perhaps leading some quick dips into the ocean. Bring a swimsuit!

An enjoyable ascent up a manageable mountain, capped with magnificent views of the SoCal area, accompanied by one of our most active and involved professors. Rebecca Broyer - lecturer, green business owner, world traveler, and surfer - will come with us on a fantastic hike up the Los Liones Trail.

Peaks and Professors' first trip! A day hike through the forested and winding paths of Malibu Creek State Park, with EALC Professor Brian Bernards, an expert in Chinese literature and film, along with study abroad, international travel, and the twists and turns comprising any career path.
